## Phase 3: Content Extraction Rules

### Mandatory Extraction Requirements

#### 1. Extract ALL Sections
You MUST extract content from:
- Abstract
- Introduction (including motivation and problem statement)
- Related Work / Background
- Methodology (complete, not summarized)
- Implementation Details (all technical specifics)
- Results / Evaluation (all metrics, benchmarks, comparisons)
- Code Examples (every single code block)
- Algorithms (complete logic, not abbreviated)
- Conclusions (all findings and future directions)
- Appendices (if present)

#### 2. Preserve Mathematical Formulas
- Convert all mathematical notation to LaTeX format
- Use `$$` for block equations
- Use `$` for inline equations
- Preserve all subscripts, superscripts, and special symbols
- Include equation numbers if present
- Document what each variable represents

#### 3. Capture Code Snippets
- Extract EVERY code block from the paper
- Identify the programming language (Python, Java, C++, JavaScript, etc.)
- Preserve code formatting and indentation
- Include comments from the code
- Note the context where each code example appears
- If code is incomplete, note that and describe what it should do

#### 4. Extract Diagrams/Figures Descriptions
- Provide detailed text descriptions of all diagrams
- Explain what the diagram illustrates
- Note relationships shown in diagrams
- Describe data flow if applicable
- Include any labels or annotations from figures

#### 5. Note Performance Metrics and Benchmarks
- Extract all numerical performance data
- Include units of measurement
- Note experimental setup
- Document comparisons with other methods
- Capture any statistical significance information

#### 6. Document Assumptions and Limitations
- Extract all stated assumptions
- Note any limitations mentioned
- Document constraints or prerequisites
- Include any caveats or warnings

